body:
This techlib is a straightforward mapping from `$_NOT_`, `$_AND_`, `$_OR_`, `$_XOR_`, and `$_MUX_` to a _k_-LUT, with configurable _k_. It is useful for experimenting with replacement of `abc`.

Combined with #717, this extremely naïve techmapper produces, in my non-rigorous tests, similar LUT density to `abc`, at a miniscule fraction of the complexity and effort. For example, the design below is synthesized as follows:
  * `abc` as invoked by `synth_ice40`: 17 `SB_LUT4`;
  * LUT techmapping: 51 `SB_LUT4`;
  * LUT techmapping followed by LUT packing via `opt_lut`: 18 `SB_LUT4`.

In addition, while right now `simplemap` and `techmap` do not seem to preserve wire names (or maybe I'm doing something wrong; haven't looked in detail yet), it seems far simpler to adjust them to do so. In that case, the naive techmapper could be greatly useful for design optimization even if it produces substantially worse logic, so long as the logic it produces is *uniformly* worse than the logic produces by `abc`.

<details>

```verilog
module top(
  input [15:0] s_a,
  input [15:0] s_b,
  output reg [16:0] s_o,
  input c_or,
  input c_and,
  input c_xor
);

always @(*) begin
  x_sel <= 2'd0;
  if (c_or)  x_sel <= 1'd1;
  if (c_and) x_sel <= 2'd2;
  if (c_xor) x_sel <= 2'd3;
end

always @(*) begin
  s_o <= 17'd0;
  case (x_sel)
    1'd0: s_o <= s_a;
    1'd1: s_o <= (s_a | s_b);
    2'd2: s_o <= (s_a & s_b);
    2'd3: s_o <= (s_a ^ s_b);
  endcase
end

endmodule
```
</details>

